Situation 1: LLM
In the case that we encounter a Large Language Model on the DMZ two members of the CPTC team will be the two Prompt Engineers. They will figure out a way to manipulate the LLM to potentially give us information that can help get access to a host outside the DMZ. 

Resources:
https://portswigger.net/web-security/llm-attacks
https://snyk.io/blog/addressing-risks-in-the-owasp-top-10-for-llms/
 

Situation 2: Phishing Campaign 
In the case where we can set up a phishing campaign to do a spear phishing attack on the client the Head of Phishing and Emails will set up this campaign. 

Resources:
https://github.com/trustedsec/social-engineer-toolkit
https://www.cyberly.org/en/how-do-you-use-set-to-perform-a-spear-phishing-attack/index.html
 

Situation 3: Cloud Platform 
In the event that we find the cloud platform that the client is using for their infrastructure two members will be discovering and exploiting the cloud resources running on the infrastructure.  

Resources:
https://github.com/sa7mon/S3Scanner
https://github.com/ine-labs/GCPGoat/tree/main/attack-manuals/module-1
https://github.com/ine-labs/AzureGoat/tree/master/attack-manuals/module-1
https://github.com/ine-labs/AWSGoat/tree/master/attack-manuals/module-1

Situation 4: Web App 
In the situation where we are faced with a web application and need to find a way into the network, team members will find a web vulnerability that we can use to exploit and gain access to the network.

Resources:
https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/
https://portswigger.net/web-security/all-materials
https://www.php.net/manual/en/book.mysql.php
https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/
https://www.w3schools.com/php/default.asp


